description:
Ok, this isn’t much of an observation, but the recent New Zealand obs., and the recent discussions of the unknown Mycena Observation #4649, reminded me of this one.

This is a tiny bright colored little guy, brought in by James Edmonds at the last BAMS ACCF, at Albion, CA. It was only about 3-4mm in diameter, and about 1.5-2cm long. Didn’t know much what to do with it, bright, and slightly waxy maybe, so we kinda put a name of Hygrocybe sp. on it. I took a photo, as I try to do, and later just put a number on it, and popped it in the drier. But since it was soo small, also all by itself, just didn’t know what to do about it, and mostly forgot about it.

But looking over the New Zealand and other Tropical observations (Ecuador maybe?), I keep seeing something like this, as perhaps a bright red Mycena.

But not sure, in the end don’t know. Haven’t seem much else like this little guy in California before or since. But thought I would toss it up here, as another possible tropical California siting, and see what people thought (or not)…

Found in grass mostly, I think some moss, and small woody debris. They are found attached to grass and small woody debris.

They appear to be brown spored, and uncertain what they are, need to get them under the scope. The cap surface is slightly granular, which is maybe interesting…

I don’t seem to have who brought these in, or where they were found, other than on the table at the end of the day. But no one in the room seemed to be able to say what these were. I think people looked at the spores and saw them as smooth and hyaline. They might be some sort of Gymnopus, but really no idea.
Found under pines, some D. fir near by.

Found under redwood, in the duff.

The first one here has strangely branched tips.

Found under mixed forest, on edge of dwarf forest.

These are brown, not grey to black. Also these have a distinct odor, fruity with burnt sugar.

Found under pine, and some other mixed forest trees (mostly on the edge of the “drawf forest”).

I think I’m going with P. atratus for western obs. of these black-grey-white Phellodon. Until someone does some type of work to show how these are different from Phellodon melaleucus, or perhaps shows they are the same…
Found on rotting log, under pine, tanoak and D. fir

Found under pines in grass. I’ve been calling these L. laccata in the past, but it was pointed out that these have fairly colorless gills, where L. laccata should have pinkish gills. At some point I wanted to look at the spores at least, but not sure when I’ll get to that.
Found under D. fir, pines, redwood.
Found under D. fir, pines, tanoak.

Found under D. fir, pine, tanoak, redwood.

Ok, these aren’t really H. camarophyllus, but it is name I’ve got from the published monographs here…

I tried to save this one, but it turned out to be too old, and fell apart over-night.

Found under redwood.

Yes, I know, but give me another name to call these, and I’ll give it a try… Or at least maybe we should take steps such that next year the appropriate samples are found, preserved and the correct obs. made to show that these was the same, another, or a variation on the known species.

Found under D. fir, pine, and redwood.

These aren’t really umbonate, but they do have some orange tones, so they are kinda look half way between H. flavescens and H. acutoconica. I think after looking at them, people decided these are more H. flavescens.

Found by Noah Siegel.

After all some discussion about what might be called H. aurantiacum here in the west, the Noah brings in this one. Mostly what people have been calling H. aurantiacum for years in the west here, the spines on the fertile surface are orange to brown. Here is an example of a case where the spines are mostly white. The white spines agree (more?) with the published description for H. aurantiacum, so is this maybe the real thing?

Found under D. fir, pine, tanoak, and redwood was near enough perhaps.

Debbie Viess already posted an obs. of these earlier, with just one photo. I’m including this obs., even if this is double counting, because these are the photos of the samples found in situ.
Found under D. fir, some pine near by.

Found on moss. Brought in by Debbie Viess. Fairly common this weekend, and several people brought in samples, this grouping were the best brought in. Not sure which variation of the species, since those details are all microscopic…

Brought in by Christian. He looked at the spores under the scope, and they were dextrinoid and had a plage. These are in the section Mycenopsis, the section which has the largest variation of spore ornamentation. These actually have spores that are fairly smooth, no warts or wrinkles, but you can see the perispore covering the spore and a resulting plage. I’ve seen these also at Pt. Reyes, where they were found on the ground with moss. Not sure how this one was found, I’m assuming with moss, but don’t know which kind, or if it was on the ground or on wood.

Found on rotting hay, in a hay bale. This was a hay bale that was off on the side yard for the Albion field station, you could actually see the bale from the lab room used for the foray display.

These are kinda weird, Galerinas found on hay, no moss, no rotting wood. This is the only time I’ve seen this. Peter Werner and I looked at them under the scope, and were able to confirm they are Galerina, but didn’t get much farther than that. I need to look at these under the scope one of these times.

Found in moss on the ground, no grass, no wood, under D. fir and pine.

These were given to Judy Rodgers to take a look at, at some point. She has seen ones that agree with G. clavata up in the Portland area, but remarked that what she sees are larger, thicker ‘shrooms than what was seen here. We both agree that they don’t really agree with the G. heterocystis description from Smith and Singer, and we’re fairly certain that we haven’t seen anything quite like G. heterocystis out there.
A few found this time, these are probably all Cystoderma amianthinum, but I wanted to at least check spore size first.
With the odor of almonds. I believe found by Debbie Viess.

Fairly rare on the coast, but a fairly good year for these. More than one person brought these in this weekend.

Found on rotting logs, under D. fir, pines, redwood.

Found on small woody debris, under D. fir, pine, tanoak. This was actually the first thing I found on Sat. morning. Got out of the car, and looked down, and there in was in the grass and debris on the side of the road. Kinda strange, with the off center stipe, and the gills are somewhat serrate.
Unknown polypore, stripped from rotting tree trunk. The fertile surface is long thin teeth, that are kinda curled around, almost like long tubes.
A complete unknown here, not even sure what genus really. White spored though…
Some unknown, found by Noah Siegel. I think we thought these my be a Clitocybe, but not sure really.

Adding some unknowns here. These were fairly numerous in this one area in the conifer duff under D. fir and pines. They are white spored, small, light tan to grey with a dark disc, hygrophanous, slightly striate when fresh.

Later I thought these might be Baeospora myosura, and looking back over the photos I’m really not sure here…
Good year for Thelephora, I know I’m still calling these T. terrestris, they are probably something else, no sure what…
Some unknown Sarcodon. Found under D. fir, tanoak, redwood. Mild taste, not strongly imbricate, dramatic fast green reaction with KOH.
Grey cap, with slight purple tone. Acrid flesh, white spores.
Found by Noah Siegel, under redwood.

Yet another orange Ramaria. Not sure how to id the orange Ramarias of the west coast, and I’ve looked at them under the scope… In any case, non-gelatinous flesh, and amyloid context. The first shot was soon after applying the Meltzer’s to the flesh, and the second was about an hour later, the amyloid reaction was quite slow.

Found on wood chips in the new landscaping of the Field Station. This was the first time for these to be added to the species list, no one worried about the little brown guys before it seems. With the new wood chips on the landscaping there were quite common this weekend.

Adding some micro-details:

The first micro-shot is of the cap surface at 400x in Meltzer’s. The cap surface is cellular, without pileocystidia, or gelatin.

The second micro-shot is of the gill edge at 400x in Meltzer’s. The cheilocystidia are lageniform to fusiod-ventricose, with acute ends. Also 4-spored basidia, no pleurocystidia, and no reactions to the reagent.

The third micro-shot is of the stipe apex at 400x in KOH. The caulocystidia are similar to the cheilocystidia, with intermixed globose elements. No cystidia obs. at the stipe base, also clamp con. obs.

The forth micro-shot is of spores from stipe apex at 1000x in KOH. Spores are ellipsoid, smooth, with a germ pore. Ave spore size : length – 9.95 +/- 0.32 (err 0.11) um, width – 5.46 +/- 0.13 um (err: 0.07) – q : 1.82 +/- 0.06, on 11 spores.

And, slightly inspired by Oluna I thought I would post my notes. Although they are going to look sparse and amateurish in comparison.
Found and id’ed by Noah Siegel. Mostly brown colors, not realy any grey or black. A slight odor of carmel.

Found under mixed conifer (maybe with tanoak?). Went back and forth on these for awhile. There are three (?) different ones that kinda match these, and there seems to be some arguments about range. Except there are a number of descriptions published it looks, and there is quite a bit of overlap on the descriptions, such that I’m not sure I could agree on a real way to split the species at all. After looking this over for awhile with Noah Siegel, kinda settled (gave up?) on this species for these.
Found on rotting wood, medium sized branches, under D. fir, pine and tanoak. Not found that often, but it was found by me and Noah Siegel this weekend, and in fair amounts.
Various unknown Nolanea obs. this weekend, here is a photo of a good large one for ya.
Found under D. fir, pine, tanoak. Actually first time found on a Fungus Fed. Foray to Albion. I would have thought these are common enough someone would have brought these in by now.
Kinda funny guy, and fairly strong white and dark guy.
Small guy found, I think first time found in a Fungus Foray to Albion. Strong smell of garlic.
Found and id’ed by Noah Siegel. Funny looking stuff.

Some unknown Inocybe, found under mixed forest of D. fir, pine, and tanoak.

These were given to J. Brown for further study.

Kinda funny seeing these. Came in with Hugh Smith (or was that another time, anyway these came in…), and I believe it was said they were found under pine.

These are rather common in the spring in the high elevations, and to find it on the coast in the winter is a little strange, or at least rare. Not sure what else these could be, they match in all ways, white, off-white gills, and a fibrous veil.

Was kinda excited to see these. There are these two deep grey Hygrophorus sited in Largent’s Hygrophorus of CA, and each of them were listed from only one sample found. One is the H. marzuolus, which is usually found in the spring up in the Sierras. I’ve seen a few of these, and have a few dried samples. Then we also lists H. camarophyllus, from the caost in the fall. I’ve heard tell of these in the past, this is the first time I was able to get a photo and a dried sample.

One thing though, the H. marzoulus is a European name, and H. camarophyllus is from the east coast. I’m not sure either of these is really one of those. I’ve seen photos of H. marzoulus, and what we see is awfully like that. I’ve also seen photos of the east coast H. camarophyllus, and they really don’t look like these.

So, not sure here. The CA samples could be two different species, or the same, and they could be different from the east coast and Europe, or the same. I guess to “prove” it would take finding a distinct character to separate them, and examining the type specimens. Which is probably beyond me.

Found on a D. fir stump.

These are kinda strange, slightly different Gymnopilus then I’ve seen before. Someday I plan on checking these under the scope.

Found on rotting wood, under pines, D. fir and tanoak.

Hugh Smith takes us out to the steam hillside, and takes us up to the top and back, and then I find this 10 feet from the car. At this site, I found as many species within 25 ft. of the car, as I did on the whole hillside. Oh, well.
Found in moss, under mixed forest of D. fir, pine, and tan oak.

A number of collections brought in of these this week, found by me, Noah Seigel and Hugh Smith. One of these was about the largest one I’ve ever seen, about 5 inches in diameter. Mostly found on D. fir logs.

Found under pine and D. fir.

Probably this one is C. amianthinum, but I would like to get it under the scope first to make sure.

I think this was the first time these were added to the species list for up there. Not sure why, I kinda think of this one as fairly common, but no one brought it is before I guess. I found an area where almost every twig in a 20 foot radius area had a few of these.

Found by Noah Siegel.

Looking at this under scope, I get the species of Crepidotus applanatus var. applanatus.

The first micro-shot is of the cap surface in radial section in Meltzer’s at 400×. This shows a cutis of compressed fibrals, with no gelatin or pileocystidia.

The second micro-shot is of the gill edge in Meltzer’s at 400×. This shows the clavate cheilocystidia. No pleurocystidia were observed.

The third micro-shot shows the spores in Meltzer’s at 1000×. Here the spores show no reaction to the reagent, they are globose with spines and about 5um in size.

Putting this together makes this Crepidotus applanatus var. applanatus.
More of this funny one that appears on grassy herbaceous stuff, not wood.
Looking at my notes, this was one of the few Corts found this weekend. There are usually a largish pile of them on the table, that we have no good idea of what to do with them.

Found on horse dung. Found by Hugh Smith.

New for me, nice a white, and kinda fuzzy. Not sure what genus these should be. This is the closest id for these, using Mushrooms Demystified.

A good collection of these found, on pine needle duff. These had a fairly interesting odor, kinda fruit and citrus on pepper and earthy. This odor is close to what is described in the Clitocybe key from D. Gregory in the monograph of CA Clitocybe, so the id as C. inversa.
Usually a mushrooms that appears early in the season, and then goes away for the rest of the year. Not sure why, this one popped up later in the season here in Jan.
A few of these out there this weekend. Small white to off-white Camarophyllus like things, with no odor.
First time this one was found in over 10 years from up there. Not sure why, this species is a little weird, in that it randomly appears sometimes early, sometimes late, and only one or two at a time…
First time this one was added to the species list for the Fungus Fed. forays to this area. Not sure why. Found this one on a log right there on the Field Station land, right next to where cars park.

I feel like I should put these in quotation marks. These were found under D. fir, and looking them over, me and Noah thought these looked like what people have been calling A. breckonii. So, you can comment on this to add your own feeling, mine are pretty soft on this one…

Anyway, I looked at these under the scope, and I post those notes at some point here. These mostly closely resemble the description for G. vexans, but the spores are the wrong size, and the cheilocystidia are slightly the wrong shape. Given other tales of identification with the Smith and Singer monograph, this makes me wonder. These could be a new species though.

Since then, one of these was brought in the ACCF by Christian Schwarz, so there are more out there, and they have a broader distribution.

Next time I see one like this, the basal tissue is going under the scope!

Microphotographs show long, knobby, tortuous pleurocystidia, sarcodimitic trama, and long, strangulate-stalked basidia.
Inamyloid, broadly elliptical spores 6.5 μm long x 4.5 μm wide, with fairly obvious hilar appendage.

Herbarium specimen is very poor. Gilbert Lab, UCSC.

CFS-31Jan2009-1 Leptonia sp.

Subgenus Cyanula, Section Caesicaules, Series Caesicaules; near the
subviduense complex.

Collected 31 Jan 2009, Mendocino County, California, USA

Cap: 31.6 mm wide, 13.8 mm high. Appressed-fibrillose, broadly convex, margin slightly inrolled and wavy. Deep midnight blue-black. Small umbo (papillate). Flesh 1.6 mm thick at disc. Dingy-white flesh.
Lamellae: 12-16 mm long, 4.2-7 mm deep. Pallid creamy-tan or flesh-colored, quite blue-gray near the stipe, somewhat marginate along the inner 1/2 of some of the larger lamellae. Approximately equal depths. Mostly straight to slightly wavy.
Stipe: 58.7 mm tall. 3.7 mm thick at apex, 3.6 mm thick at lowest point. Medium blue-gray, quite a bit lighter than cap. Glabrous except for distinct scurfs at apex. Striate at base, with distinct mycelial bulb at base – 7.6 mm thick.
Odor: (After 2 days of storage in a tacklebox) – faintly fragrant-pungent or indistinct.
Spores: (10-13.5) 12.1 μm x 6.9 (5.7-7.7) μm, 5-6 sided, heterodiametric.
Pileipellis: Trichodermium, entangled elements (collapsed ?) periclinal at disc, erect away from disc (this seems the opposite of the usual to me).
Stipitipellis: With tufts of cylindrical-clavate caulocystidia.
Cheilocystidia: Collapsed, not abundant, cylindrical-clavate to subcapitate.
Pleurocystidia: Scattered, cyclindrico-clavate, approximately 25 μm tall.
Clamp connections: Absent in all tissues examined (pilepellis, lamellae, stipe, mycelium at base of stipe)

These species can be eliminated by AT LEAST the indicated characteristic (and usually many others):
parva: different pilepellis and pileus color
yatesii: decurrent lamellae
viridiflavipes: color of stipe base, clustered habit
chalybea: basal mycelium scarce to absent, stipe “perfectly” glabrous, pilepellis a palisade
decolorans f. atropruinosipes: stipe covered in dark squamules
decolorans f. decolorans: glabrous stipe
decolorans f. cystidiosa: lacks pleurocystidia, different pilepellis

The L. subviduense group is close but the varieties differ at least in these characteristics:

var. subviduense: Lamellae most often with a decurrent tooth, rarely pruinose at apex, stipe quite fragile, smaller spores.
var. marginata: Cheilocystidia abundant – originate as elements of pileal margin when young and thus identical to pileocystidia, gills serrulate, strongly marginate, stipe “extremely fragile”.

Specimen at UCSC Gilbert Lab.

Cap 7-8 mm wide, 5-6.5 mm tall. Conical-convex. Quite bright yellow when moist, strongly hygrophanous to dull beige tan. Margin prominently striate, striations darker yellow-brown.

Stipe 29-35.5 mm tall, 1.5 mm thick. Dull yellow, scurfy-pruinose at apex.

Spores rusty orange brown, 9.3 × 5.5μm, ellipsoid, wall ~0.5 μm thick. Is that a germ pore?
My lack of experience with the genus makes it hard to decide whether there is a plage…

description: This is a hydroid in the genus Eudendrium that was quite abundant at Scott Creek last weekend. I'd never seen it before, and yet there it was, large and in charge. Saw one with a Hermissenda chomping away (pics were awful), and this one was on the side of a boulder, maybe 10-15 cm tall. John pointed it out as a "Christmas Tree Hydroid," which seems like as good a name as any. It's even ornamented! Light's Manual lists Eudendrium californicum and Eudendrium spp., noting that there have been several species reported from the area that haven't been conclusively identified. I don't see the heavy annulation that's supposed to be present on E. californicum, so I'll stick to the genus. I mean, it's a hydroid. I am psyched to have a genus. Also, if, like me, you appreciate a good little bit of hilariously inscrutable technical writing, you will enjoy this utter gem from Light's: Species of this genus are characterized by typically styloid gonophores, trumpet-shaped hypostomes, and absense of desmonemes in the cnidome. Priceless!
